.TH pam_facial_auth 8 "November 2025" "pam_facial_auth 1.0" "System Administration Utilities"
.SH NAME
pam_facial_auth \- PAM module providing face recognition authentication
.SH SYNOPSIS
Add to
.I /etc/pam.d/system-auth
or
.I /etc/pam.d/login
the line:
.PP
.B auth sufficient pam_facial_auth.so [options]
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B pam_facial_auth
module performs face recognitionâ€“based authentication within the Linux
PAM framework.

The module loads a user-specific trained model and captures live webcam
frames to verify identity. Haar-based face detection is used unless
replaced by a future DNN-based detector.

If authentication succeeds, control returns to PAM with
.B PAM_SUCCESS.
Failure returns
.B PAM_AUTH_ERR
unless configured otherwise.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B debug
Enable verbose diagnostics.
.TP
.B ignore\_unknown
If no facial model exists for the user, skip this module without failing.
.TP
.B ignore\_failure
Return success even if authentication fails.
(For debugging only.)
.TP
.B config=PATH
Specify a custom configuration file instead of
.I /etc/security/pam_facial.conf .
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/security/pam_facial.conf
Module configuration file.
.TP
.I /etc/pam_facial_auth/models/*.xml
Trained recognition models.
.TP
.I /etc/pam_facial_auth/images/*/
Captured face images.
.SH RETURN VALUES
.TP
.B PAM_SUCCESS
User authenticated.
.TP
.B PAM_AUTH_ERR
Authentication failed.
.TP
.B PAM_IGNORE
Module skipped due to configuration or missing model.
.SH NOTES
The webcam must be accessible by the process invoking PAM
(e.g., display manager, login service).
